questions.question:
A SQL analyst runs the following T-SQL command on a lakehouse's SQL analytics endpoint:

GRANT SELECT ON dbo.PatientRecords TO [analyst@company.com];

What does this command do?

An admin runs the following T-SQL commands in sequence:

GRANT SELECT ON dbo.SalesData TO [analyst@company.com];
DENY SELECT ON dbo.SalesData TO [analyst@company.com];

What is the effective permission for the analyst on the SalesData table?

An admin needs to remove a previously granted SELECT permission from a user without explicitly blocking future grants. Which T-SQL command should be used?

Option A: DENY SELECT ON dbo.Reports TO [analyst@company.com];
Option B: REVOKE SELECT ON dbo.Reports FROM [analyst@company.com];
Option C: DROP USER [analyst@company.com];
Option D: GRANT SELECT ON dbo.Reports TO [analyst@company.com];

An admin applies dynamic data masking to a table:

ALTER TABLE dbo.Employees
ALTER COLUMN SSN ADD MASKED WITH (FUNCTION = 'partial(0, "XXX-XX-", 4)');

ALTER TABLE dbo.Employees
ALTER COLUMN Salary ADD MASKED WITH (FUNCTION = 'default()');

A standard analyst (without UNMASK permission) runs SELECT SSN, Salary FROM dbo.Employees. What do they see?

An admin needs to restrict an analyst to see only the 'ProductID' and 'ProductName' columns from the Products table, hiding 'CostPrice'. Which T-SQL approach implements column-level security?

Option A: GRANT SELECT ON dbo.Products TO [analyst@company.com];
Option B: GRANT SELECT ON dbo.Products (ProductID, ProductName) TO [analyst@company.com];
Option C: DENY SELECT ON dbo.Products (CostPrice) TO [analyst@company.com];

An admin runs the following T-SQL permissions sequence for a contractor:

-- Grant access
GRANT SELECT ON dbo.ProjectData TO [contractor@external.com];
GRANT SELECT ON dbo.TeamDirectory TO [contractor@external.com];
DENY SELECT ON dbo.Salaries TO [contractor@external.com];
DENY SELECT ON dbo.HRRecords TO [contractor@external.com];

-- Project ends
REVOKE SELECT ON dbo.ProjectData FROM [contractor@external.com];
REVOKE SELECT ON dbo.TeamDirectory FROM [contractor@external.com];

After all statements execute, what is the contractor's effective access?
